</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="65731EB17AFF276D8E713C8637826452" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="diagnosis">
<paragraph id="68491794E91C943FA225066CC8DB87E0" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Diagnosis.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="AB1D8262EB8C25F08D7E338D9A0D03A0" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Occipital carina weakly lamelliform dorsally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C4736279BE83B7CA56A0626A01B72009" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2C</figureCitation>
); supra-antennal elevations about 0.2 times as long as scapus and largely ivory dorsally (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5D093EF61158F1ED8B85062D0812AD58" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2C</figureCitation>
); frons densely punctate (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DB12A5301985811B2F01E2BEA0646D23" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2C</figureCitation>
); mandible mainly black, except dark brown base of teeth (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="885271800A9DF779EF06EDA010A70810" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2B</figureCitation>
); mesoscutum and propodeum distinctly sculptured; metasoma robust, smooth and largely black except the posterior half of first tergite ivory (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="C3D56637404CEC054DE98E0E62836941" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2A</figureCitation>
); first tergite approximately as long as its apical width (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="742C07AE458F0FF710C45A003B0B4E14" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3F</figureCitation>
); third sternite approximately 0.5 
<normalizedToken id="7547565821FC2B676577F222D2C35471" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as second sternite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DB6BCBD24AACFA4CB54BB8FC00CC364B" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3H</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="6C5284A78FB2220F00CD7C1C27D4D640" doi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" start="Figure 2" startId="F2">
<paragraph id="22516AAB89BE5B32E99948E2CA1EA5C3" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="0A74E2B85E20E2582794ABDB82AF8CFF" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Figure 2.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D9B9486C3CB421C0035CC3FFF5C044B7" authority="Tsuneki, 1991" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Jezonogonalos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jezonogonalos eburnalva" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eburnalva">
<emphasis id="6F2C4B8CE05F6C87ABDDC4506C33C513" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Jezonogonalos eburnalva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En-419020) 
<emphasis id="C2A069070EC020C3EC84C099082A4F25" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">A</emphasis>
habitus, lateral aspect 
<emphasis id="0E62408D5D36ACFB75F7E527ECEC2632" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">B</emphasis>
head, anterior aspect 
<emphasis id="6B73754F4CA9B9CB27C99DE1B9F7C6E8" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">C</emphasis>
head, dorsal aspect.
</paragraph>
</caption>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="40B43551F659ACF0EB213E8A3680ADD1" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="description">
<paragraph id="6BF71110F80E33D87C937C969597F557" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Description.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="9F0F2EE8DEEB80C7B763277B8537E93C" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="5597A34166660E5212EDE0DE6AD0214D" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Male.</emphasis>
Holotype, length of body 6.2 mm (of fore wing 5.1 mm).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="1C5F1884DA92F4646847663B8EA08627" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="4FBB8920D36063150677C90A01977FE5" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="2A200D2CEC7148EFD3C2E5791B8DD419" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Colour</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Black; lower half of inner orbita narrowly ivory and connected to ivory malar space (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F8B7A47113998383BAE9832489F96562" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2B</figureCitation>
); apex of supra-antennal elevation ivory (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8FF574E7864D3A63EB74CE8409901C7C" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2B</figureCitation>
); lateral corner of clypeus ivory and connected to ivory malar space; mandibular teeth, palpi dark brown (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A6412CE89C702DDB844744EF0F5FBFAA" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2B</figureCitation>
); tegulae dark brown; legs mainly black, but tibia and tarsus of fore leg rather brownish (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="8F4117AC0D5AD3FE1827C060D85162C3" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2A</figureCitation>
); apical half of first tergite ivory in dorsal view, nearly all of first tergite ivory in lateral view (Figs 
<figureCitation id="EE68F9CF720417F21BEF0B64903B6756" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3F, G</figureCitation>
) and apico-lateral margin of first sternite ivory (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5BBFFAF865A7707AB69748E083CEB9A3" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3H</figureCitation>
); posterior margin of all other tergites and sternites light ivory (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="A218B8DACC54CC369B5786989B1C1459" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3H</figureCitation>
); pterostigma and posterior half of first submarginal cell to anterior third of marginal cell of fore wing and area below it dark brown to light brown, remainder of wing membrane subhyaline (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="32231F247532831C8E7404A1AC819A63" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<caption id="95BF7166CF9A069D5CB50B0E4E62EB3B" doi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" start="Figure 3" startId="F3">
<paragraph id="A213C7318484160BF599172092230331" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="377EA1B19B447A7A28C721E0F5DA97BA" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Figure 3.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName id="D8E7215B695D7A309FF63F5558718A89" authority="Tsuneki, 1991" authorityName="Zhang &amp; Chen" authorityYear="2022" class="Insecta" family="Trigonalyidae" genus="Jezonogonalos" higherTaxonomySource="GBIF" kingdom="Animalia" lsidName="Jezonogonalos eburnalva" order="Hymenoptera" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="eburnalva">
<emphasis id="7E278789FB7EAEE1CA238B4487D8A1CC" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Jezonogonalos eburnalva</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En-419020) 
<emphasis id="2B1473CB3CC28138861A985347F11EF7" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">A</emphasis>
tyloids on 10th-16th segments of antenna 
<emphasis id="1ACE290FD9776DCBD1A09A265170973E" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">B</emphasis>
wings 
<emphasis id="5335C5C289751C000C2DCFA96836A117" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">C</emphasis>
head, lateral aspect 
<emphasis id="5C065EB4FC662602D4C7D84F7B1ABA6C" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">D</emphasis>
mesosoma, dorsal aspect 
<emphasis id="C2C79EA6647DC43393803648E065D977" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">E</emphasis>
mesosoma, lateral aspect 
<emphasis id="7C5E730E709F5773D6CB5983DB5FC338" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">F</emphasis>
metasoma, dorsal aspect 
<emphasis id="AA12B0998B1FC65A75C9732014F23463" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">G</emphasis>
metasoma, lateral aspect 
<emphasis id="6D0E7FAA8885FFB563C65C4328F1BAB6" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">H</emphasis>
metasoma, ventral aspect.
</paragraph>
</caption>
<paragraph id="E7E5606A203125E5998D8E6F3BF121F9" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="49C73D2C3ECFFFFBB95B06D867CEC519" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="C358513580E94EA91A86F152AF42E925" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Head</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Antenna with 24 segments (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="9156A12DEA108C62BA2622C51334851A" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2A</figureCitation>
); tyloids nearly circular on 10th, 15th and 16th segments, oval on 11th-14th segments, 0.1 times as long as segment on 10th, 16th segments and 0.3 times as long as segments on 11th-15th segments (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DD9161C23B607140265ABE5856987EBC" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3A</figureCitation>
); frons densely punctate; vertex and temple largely smooth and shiny with sparse and fine punctures; head gradually narrowed behind eyes, eye in dorsal view approximately as long as temple (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="12CCF05022674C94D9F0DBB2F80371FD" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2C</figureCitation>
); occipital carina narrow lamelliform medio-dorsally and without crenulae; supra-antennal elevations enlarged (about 0.2 
<normalizedToken id="060EB1CB656D91793BCA44DD367A8D6D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as scapus), outer side subvertical and largely smooth except for sparse punctures (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="6496F08CD7A9E72EA68DA804EA688DA2" captionStart="Figure 2" captionStartId="F2" captionText="Figure 2. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A habitus, lateral aspect B head, anterior aspect C head, dorsal aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure2" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677739" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">2C</figureCitation>
); clypeus slightly concave and thick medio-ventrally.
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="B831B986AA482AC0BBA146C4A07AED24" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="D0177B8464943BEB90B8AA3E10C01D0B" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="97AF6F876B770DE379FFB76D725D2434" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Mesosoma</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Length of mesosoma 1.8 
<normalizedToken id="E78D287AA6A956D779944E20DC48D7E1" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as its height (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="B143F082F918B7AEF6084BBF94FB81C9" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3E</figureCitation>
); mesopleuron smooth anteriorly and transversely reticulate-rugose posteriorly, transverse mesopleural groove moderately wide and shallow (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="F44D9585D91CFC69D42A26B1E07F0CD3" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3E</figureCitation>
); notauli wide, deep and coarsely crenulate; middle lobe of mesoscutum transversely rugose, lateral lobes of mesoscutum mainly finely rugose with a shallow furrow medially (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="5EA343739B5A891E2AFD4C6E3B5C87B5" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3D</figureCitation>
); scutellar sulcus wide and coarsely crenulate; scutellum shiny, largely smooth with irregular longitudinal rugae, slightly convex medially and anteriorly near level of mesoscutum (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="1726B40847FE641CB6DE31DA50B006F8" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3E</figureCitation>
); metanotum medially protruding and obtuse, shiny and largely smooth with sparse fine rugae (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="84EF1F313E5AEACBA070E5B2F18E002A" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3D</figureCitation>
); propodeum reticulate-rugose antero-medially, obliquely rugulose antero-laterally, distinct transversely striate medially, with several longitudinal striae and sparse irregular rugae between large smooth space posteriorly (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="2A258B0B0DE88472DB7F75A9970CF2CD" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3D</figureCitation>
); posterior propodeal carina thick lamelliform (foramen approximately1.4 
<normalizedToken id="D4ECEFEDCD42291B456E7B263E414166" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as wide as high medially).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="E5F3C612C748E17D46D901B65D06228C" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="7D4C3641792A381E75DB4AEE27AFC72A" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="CE7177334B79705E94DE0EA3084E6BF2" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Wings</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
Fore wing: length of vein 1-M 1.6 
<normalizedToken id="E002C1538DD0D722ADDCAEBCD5EE5503" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as vein 1-SR; second submarginal cell 3.1 
<normalizedToken id="B4425A44198B809C7B11D14468149F5D" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as third submarginal cell (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="DF723895F13F9B0729BF29A15FD3F59C" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3B</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="0C07ED67F8005FEE8A2552CCB028EAD8" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="F393A3DDD19D4988C14937678749290B" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="6C1DCCEC53EDF4D34762E6D271A623E7" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Metasoma</emphasis>
.
</emphasis>
First tergite approximately as long as its apical width, smooth and with distinct elliptical depression antero-medially, apical half with fine dense longitudinal rugae; second and following tergites shiny and smooth except for sparse superficial punctures (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="AB9AD1C2CFA336045CF9C68D6B582BE7" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3F</figureCitation>
); sternites rather sparsely finely punctate; second sternite rather flat; third sternite approximately 0.5 
<normalizedToken id="A168F1D295A66154595291BEF52DCD07" originalValue="×">x</normalizedToken>
as long as second sternite (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="0CD314C7CE2F337814B9BAB8DA17FCD8" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3H</figureCitation>
); genitalia extruded (Fig. 
<figureCitation id="51B662D6FCAD51D71695CA79B40A02F7" captionStart="Figure 3" captionStartId="F3" captionText="Figure 3. Jezonogonalos eburnalva Zhang &amp; Chen, sp. nov., holotype, male (En- 419020) A tyloids on 10 th- 16 th segments of antenna B wings C head, lateral aspect D mesosoma, dorsal aspect E mesosoma, lateral aspect F metasoma, dorsal aspect G metasoma, lateral aspect H metasoma, ventral aspect." figureDoi="10.3897/jhr.90.80150.figure3" httpUri="https://binary.pensoft.net/fig/677740" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">3G</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph id="08F6E8D7C81A8D81EF514AEB19E15A5F" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
<emphasis id="C92B78E4B54E868F4FBE868B54CC89AE" bold="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Female.</emphasis>
Unknown.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection id="47F349A18D911618F73CEA41DB3B5E37" pageId="0" pageNumber="101" type="etymology">
<paragraph id="EFAE61750EAABC812559FC77B9821D1F" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">Etymology.</paragraph>
<paragraph id="7ADB8ECAEBD39A045697C5E87DCC7238" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">
Name derived from &quot; 
<emphasis id="4843258392F4EBB2C0B3DF0D90F42280" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">eburnus</emphasis>
&quot; (Latin for 
<normalizedToken id="E6777C1F94D8573C0E98E4AFD1497BDF" originalValue="“ivory”">&quot;ivory&quot;</normalizedToken>
) and &quot; 
<emphasis id="8F5BB94857F138A07AF50851B82E8D88" italics="true" pageId="0" pageNumber="101">alvus</emphasis>
&quot; (Latin for 
<normalizedToken id="831192E8F2BAC6438C071440C07B7D01" originalValue="“belly”">&quot;belly&quot;</normalizedToken>
) because of the large ivory area of the first tergite.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
